definition.value: A mannosylinositol phosphorylceramide in which the sphingoid moiety is specified as dihydroceramide.

An amino oligosaccharide that is a branched dodecasaccharide derivative comprising N-acetylneuraminic acid, D-galactose, N-acetyl-D-glucosamine and D-mannoseD residues linked as shown. It constitutes the N-glycan moiety in human thyroglobulin.

A flavanone glycoside that is eriodictyol attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage. It is an Nrf2 activator and provides protection against cisplatin-induced toxicity.
A sulfone that is a metabolite of dapsone in which one of the amino groups of dapsone has been oxidized to a nitroso group.
A chromenol that is 2-(3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)-4H-1-benzopyran carrying four additional hydroxy substituents at positions 3, 4, 5 and 7.
A chromenol that is 2-(4-hydroxyphenyl)-4H-1-benzopyran carrying four additional hydroxy substituents at positions 3, 4, 5 and 7.
A secondary carboxamide resulting from acetylation of one of the amino groups of dapsone.
A sulfone that is dapsone in which both of the amino groups been acetylation. An antimicrobial drug, it also has antimalarial activity.
An acetamide that is acetaminophen (paracetamol) substituted on the phenolic oxygen and the amido nitrogen with trimethylsilyl groups
A triterpenoid saponin in which the triterpenoid fragment can be any cucurbitane derivative.
A polyprenol diphosphate having (Z,Z,Z)-geranylgeraniyl (nerylneryl) as the polyprenyl component.
A tryptamine alkaloid that is tryptamine carrying an additional phosphoryloxy substituent at position 4.
A diterpenoid that is (+)-kolavelool in which the tertiary hydroxy hydrogen has been replaced by a methyl group.
A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-tryptophan in which the hydrogen at position 5 of the indole ring has been replaced by a chlorine.
The L-alpha-amino-acid residue derived from piperacilloyl-L-lysine.
The L-alpha-amino-acid residue derived from flucloxacilloyl-L-lysine.
The L-alpha-amino-acid residue derived from amoxicillin-L-lysine.
The L-alpha-amino-acid residue derived from benzylpenicilloyl-L-lysine.
The L-alpha-amino-acid residue derived from aztreonyl-L-lysine.
A chemical compound that causes a substantial proportion of exposed people or animals to develop an allergic reaction in normal tissue after repeated exposure to the compound.

An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue derived from N(4)-[alpha-D-Man-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[alpha-D-Man-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[alpha-D-Man-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc]-L-Asn.

A diterpene that is cyclotetradeca-1,3,7,11-tetraene which is substituted by methyl groups at positions 1, 7, and 11, and by an isopropyl group at position 4 (the 1Z,3E,7E,11E isomer). It is a constituent of the essential oils from Pinus koraiensis and Pinus sibirica.
An inorganic sodium salt in which the counteranion is tetrachloropalladate(2-).
